               <history>

                  <origin>
                     <origPlace cert="medium" evidence="internal">According to the colophon, the
                        scribe hailed from ʿAqrah (<foreign xml:lang="ara">عقرة</foreign>
                        <foreign xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc">ʿAqra</foreign> in Arabic; <foreign
                           xml:lang="kur">ئاكرێ</foreign>
                        <foreign xml:lang="kur">Akrê</foreign> in modern Kurdish), though we cannot
                        be sure if this is where the manuscript was produced </origPlace>
                     <origDate notBefore="1819-03-01" notAfter="1819-03-18" calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                        >late Jumādā al-awwal 1234</origDate>
                     <origDate notBefore="1819-03-01" notAfter="1819-03-18" calendar="#Gregorian"
                        >early March 1819</origDate> -- though the word read as <foreign
                        xml:lang="ara">مائتین</foreign> (200) has been smudged, and might also be
                     read as <foreign xml:lang="ara">مائة</foreign> (100), yeilding 1722 as opposed
                     to 1819. Still, the presence of an amīr named Ismāʿīl Pasha in the region of
                     ʿAqrah in the early half of the 1800s suggests the former reading is more
                     likely.</origin>

                  <provenance>According to the colophon, made for a certain <persName key="person_f8582" role="fmo"><persName
                           xml:lang="kur">Mūsá Bēg bin Ismāʿīl Paşa</persName> <persName xml:lang="kur">موسی بیک بن اسماعیل پاشا</persName></persName>
                     -- the latter possibly referring to <persName key="person_f8583" role="subject"><persName
                        xml:lang="kur">Amīr Ismāʿīl Paşa I of Zakho</persName> <persName xml:lang="kur">اسماعیل پاشا</persName></persName>.</provenance>

                  <acquisition>A note on the inside of the front cover reads "<quote>Bt (1.3.09)
                        from <persName key="person_f1654" role="fmo">J. J.
                        Naaman</persName>".</quote></acquisition>


               </history>

